recordings.loc: Escanaba Township (near  Flat Rock), Delta County, Michigan
recordings.rmk: Unmodified recording. This recording followed XC736761 and was made by walking into a meadow of tall grass. This recording is simply two near buzzes (without the warbles that were recorded on XC736761). The buzzes are preceded by extremely short soft notes on different pitches and followed immediately by a different note. The bird must have been very near, but hidden in the tall grass.

recordings.loc: Escanaba Township (near  Flat Rock), Delta County, Michigan
recordings.rmk: Replaced 12 seconds of static with 1 second silence (at 2:46-2:58 on original recording), otherwise unmodified.  Walked out into meadow of tall grass which upset the deer (who snorted intermittently but then resumed foraging). High tinkling songs suggested Grasshopper Sparrow nearby, and the recording has three of these before any buzz. Complex songs of buzz plus warbles are best at 39 sec. and 4:11 sec., but there are multiple other complex songs on the recording. A moment after I ended the recording, the bird made two loud buzzes, which are on a separate recording, XC736762.

Moore Creek Preserve (near  Santa Cruz), Santa Cruz County, California
recordings.rmk: This wasn't modified significantly to my knowledge, other than cutting out some extraneous noise and boosting the audio. I observed this bird in an open, grassy environment. I don't have too many specifics on plants, but I recall the non-native wild oat and possibly quaking-grass being present. Notably, Moore Creek features a herd of cattle, used to "cow-scape" the area by helping remove invasive plants and reduce the risk of fires. As is typical for the species, this sparrow was singing close to the ground.  I'd assume this bird is male, since I haven't heard of female Grasshopper Sparrows with a complex song. It was observed on a cloudy day, bordering on foggy, and it was somewhat cold outside.

recordings.rmk: Presumed perpallidus subspecies based on photos (see eBird checklist of a 2nd bird in the area at this link: http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S38293861). While ammolegus subspecies is the resident breeding form in southeastern Arizona, the perpallidus subspecies has casually bred in north-central Arizona previously. This record is a new location for the species, especially notable as an indicator of potential local breeding. This is the same bird as recording XC381894. recordings.file-name: XC252861-Male and Female GRSP on Levee 2 Miles South of Bass Landing Road, MS 06-15-15.mp3
recordings.rmk: GRSP on Levee south of Desoto River Park.  Bird heard singing on the levee.  Used playback and the bird responded with it's own singing.  Two GRSP's then appeared on road and began posturing to one another in a bobbing manner.  They then flew down the levee together and both began to sing.  The male sang the typical "trill" song while the female followed with a quieter "female trill" song as described by Smith, R. (1959). The Songs of the Grasshopper Sparrow. Wilson Bulletin, 71(2), 141-152.

recordings.loc: North Grand River Trails, Brantford, Ontario
recordings.rmk:
Bird perched on a plastic post in the middle of a grassy, overgrown abandoned quarry. Interestingly, this individual was stomping its right foot while flapping its left wing - a peculiar behavior I've not seen before! Determined to be male by behavior, singing atop various high perches. 

This stretch of habitat has become increasingly valuable over the years as the quarry has grown over. At least ten pairs of Grasshopper Sparrow now breed here each year. A second male can be heard in the background of this recording, and there were at least four within the vicinity at the time of this recording.

recordings.loc: Avon Park Air Force Range, Highlands County, Florida
recordings.rmk:
Recorded using Nokia Lumia 635 with Audio Recorder HiFi app; edited with Audacity: high-pass filter, noise reduction, and volume amplification.

This recording shows two Grasshopper Sparrows counter-singing and calling from opposite sides of the main road at APAFR.  One of the two birds was observed visually at a distance of approximately 30m through Nikon Monarch 5 10x40 binoculars.  The bird was perched atop a low palmetto bush surrounded by grasses and sedges.  This location was a past home to a small population of Florida Grasshopper Sparrows (A. s. floridanus), but this population was believed extirpated by around 2010.  While I believe this may be the floridanus subspecies, given that it is unlikely migrant A. m. pratensis would be singing and counter-singing on "territory" if they are in the process of migrating north; however, I was unable to observe any bands on the bird I saw visually - a clear indication of Florida Grasshopper Sparrow.  This may be due to the distance I was observing this bird; more information is needed before conclusively narrowing this down to subspecies.

Mainly cloudy skies, wind ESE at 3mph, open grassland with sporadic palmetto and nearby cypress head, 19°C

recordings.loc: Bonito Prairie, Rt. 71 south of Rt. 70 and east of East Bonito Prairie Tank, White Mountain Apache Reservation,  Apache County, Arizona
recordings.rmk: Apparent perpallidus subspecies based on photos. While ammolegus is the resident subspecies that breeds in southeastern Arizona, the perpallidus subspecies has casually bred at isolated locations in north-central Arizona previously. This is a first record of the species for this area, especially notable as an indicator of potential breeding locally. Photos of the bird can be seen on my eBird checklist at this link: http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist/S38293861. Amplification, noise reduction, and high pass filter used in Audacity.

recordings.rmk: Shortgrass prairie ecosystem, in a moist bottom with thick tall grasses. Adultswere nearby, but this call note ("zeek") came from a presumed fledgling(s), based on incomplete tail growth noted when flushed.
